<h2>Further reading and credible sources</h2>
<p>You’ll get the most reliable picture by combining archival research, oral histories, and published secondary sources. Below are the kinds of sources I recommend you consult:</p>
<ul>
<li>Railway archives and transport museums (national and municipal)</li>
<li>Local newspapers and contemporaneous reporting for crash reports and dates</li>
<li>Oral-history collections housed in local historical societies</li>
<li>War and POW archives (for sites like the Death Railway)</li>
<li>Ballad and oral tradition collections in ethnographic repositories</li>
<li>Scholarly work on memory studies, industrial archaeology, and heritage tourism</li>
</ul>
<p>When you read folklore collections or listen to ballads, pay attention to transmission chains: who told the story to whom, and how it changed over time. That will tell you why a particular train became “ghostly.”</p>
